{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The scoring model assigns the correct risk score when a transaction exceeds the configured amount threshold for its merchant category.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Minimum failure boundary is local rule evaluation (threshold lookup by merchant category + score computation) and can be exercised with in-memory config/transaction fixtures. MOCK-MISS check: this behavior does not require cross-module state handoff by its text. REAL-INFRA/LLM/MULTI-STEP: none required. Rejected higher level: behavior text is strictly deterministic rule logic (\"configured amount threshold\" and \"assigns correct risk score\"), so no real OS/network/model output is needed. Adversarial critique: if threshold resolution actually depends on repository/config service wiring, Integration would be needed; that dependency is not stated in the behavior.","test_description":"Call the scoring function with category-specific threshold config and a transaction amount just above threshold; assert exact numeric score contribution and final score. Add boundary assertions at threshold and just below threshold to catch off-by-one logic.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The risk model identifies a fraudulent transaction pattern (e.g., rapid small purchases from different geographies) even when no single rule threshold is exceeded.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real model judgment quality (classification of a cross-signal fraud pattern), not just plumbing. A stubbed model would always pass and hide true false-negative/false-positive behavior (LLM-DEP/MOCK-HIDE). Not Workflow: only one agentic decision is required, not multiple agentic steps chained. Rejected Integration because behavior text explicitly tests what the model \"identifies,\" not routing/retry/payload mechanics. Adversarial critique: if this \"risk model\" is actually a fixed deterministic rules engine, Integration/Unit could suffice; behavior wording frames it as predictive model output.","test_description":"Run the real risk model on a curated labeled set containing multi-geo rapid small-purchase patterns where single rule thresholds are not exceeded; assert detection meets agreed fraud-probability threshold/recall target for this slice.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The velocity check in the scoring model correctly counts the number of transactions within the configured time window per user.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure commonly appears at module boundary between scoring logic and transaction-history retrieval/window filtering (timestamp boundaries, per-user scoping, ordering). Unit tests on pure counting logic can miss query/filter handoff bugs (MOCK-MISS). Integration is sufficient with local DB or in-process repository fake; no real OS/network/subprocess needed (INTEGRATION-BRAKE a: no). No AI/ML dependence (b: no), no multi-agent chain (c: no). Rejected System because behavior text only requires correct window count semantics, not real infrastructure behavior. Adversarial critique: if history is already passed as a prepared list into one function, Unit would be enough.","test_description":"Wire scoring service to repository/local DB fixture; seed multiple users and edge timestamps (inside, outside, and exactly at window boundary). Execute velocity check and assert per-user count used in score matches expected window semantics.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A transaction flagged by the risk model but not by the scoring model is still held for review — the models operate as an OR gate, not AND.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is orchestration logic across two module outputs and review-hold decision state. Use deterministic stubs for model outputs to isolate gate logic; behavior does not require validating model quality itself. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: no real OS/network/subprocess; no dependence on model output quality content beyond boolean/probability inputs; no multi-agent chain. Rejected Agentic: behavior text tests gate semantics (\"OR gate, not AND\"), not whether risk predictions are correct. Adversarial critique: if hold decision is enforced only by an external workflow engine/API, System might be required.","test_description":"Construct end-to-end service call with scoring result=not flagged and risk result=flagged; assert final decision is HOLD_FOR_REVIEW. Add inverse case (scoring flagged, risk not) and neither flagged to verify truth table.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.07,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The combined output includes both the numeric risk score and the risk model's fraud probability, so the reviewer can see which model flagged the transaction and why.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is data-contract composition across modules: scoring output + risk output + reviewer-facing explanation fields. Unit tests of a single mapper may miss schema/field-name mismatches between producers and aggregator. No real OS/network required; no need for real model quality evaluation because fixed outputs can validate contract shape/content presence. Rejected Agentic because behavior text focuses on combined payload completeness/attribution, not correctness of model judgment. Adversarial critique: if output contract is built entirely in one pure function with typed inputs, Unit could be sufficient.","test_description":"Run aggregator/service with fixed scoring and risk model responses; assert response includes numeric score, fraud probability, per-model flag indicators, and explanation fields that correctly attribute which model triggered review.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.06,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
